The significant disruption, amplified by a failing and financial crippling healthcare system for citizens/workers, will inevitably lead to negative real GDP growth in 2020, and the repercussions will be felt for years to come. This is just the beginning--the market is behaving semi-erratically because little is known about how this pandemic will play out, but the reality is the world and its politics are much more complicated today than they were during the Flu pandemic of the 20th century, and in a global culture preoccupied with eternal growth, disruption will be even more significant.

Last week, I forecasted an 85% probability the United States would experience at least one quarter of negative real GDP growth in 2020. Looking at the last time the quarter-on-quarter U.S. GDP growth rate was negative, which was Q1 2014, I also saw estimates of first and second quarter growth at around -10% and -25%. Considering the unprecedented rise in the unemployment rate, consumer spending, foreign trade, and other financial/economic factors influenced by COVID-19, I would now increase my forecast to 95%. Since last week, jobless claims surged and BofA economists forecast that the unemployment rate will soon hit 15.6% from 3.5% as of February, which would by far outstrip the unemployment rate during the 2007-09 recession. “The Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, -1.68% has lost 25% year to date through Thursday. That includes a first-quarter decline of 23.2%, which was the worst one-quarter performance for the index since the fourth quarter of 1987.” A deep global recession in 2020 is now Fitch Ratings’ baseline forecast according to its latest update of its Global Economic Outlook (GEO) forecasts. Bank of America Global Research also said it expects the COVID-19-related recession in the U.S. to be the “deepest recession on record,” nearly five times worse than the postwar average.

To predict the possibility of the United States experiencing at least one quarter of negative real GDP growth in 2020, I looked at the last time the quarter-on-quarter U.S. GDP growth rate was negative, which was Q1 2014. “The decrease in real GDP in the first quarter primarily reflected negative contributions from private inventory investment, exports, state and local government spending, nonresidential fixed investment, and residential fixed investment that were partly offset by a positive contribution from PCE. Imports increased”. -Additionally, as COVID-19 cuts through the economy, IHS Market forecasts a 2nd quarter GDP growth plunging to -13%, GDP contracting 1.7% in 2020 (year over year), unemployment approaching 9% by December, and inflation slipping to 1.3% in 2021. JPMorgan dragged its first-quarter growth estimate to -10% from -4% and dropped its second-quarter estimate to -25% from -14%. -“One way to compute this is to cumulate the difference between GDP in this updated forecast and GDP in the most recent forecast that did not show significant effects of the pandemic. Using this method we estimate that, over the next five years, the pandemic will cost the economy $1.5 trillion (2012 dollars) in foregone GDP. Hence, the cost of the pandemic continues to rise even after the economy regains full employment, albeit at a much slower pace than during the recession itself.” -It is important to stay current on foreign growth, energy (essentially oil prices), consumer spending, auto shutdown, unemployment, initial financial conditions, monetary policy, and fiscal policy, when considering GDP growth and forecasting economic costs/changes during the COVID-19 pandemic.

Recessions or just one quarter of negative growth (a recession is generally defined as two quarters of negative growth) is very likely in 2020. Normally, a recession begins in one of two cases. There is a fear of too much growth resulting in inflation, and the government slows the economy by means of reducing aggregate demand using increased interest rates, decreased the money supply, higher taxes or reduced government spending. The greater the inflation risk, the greater the attempt to reduce inflation and the likelihood of a recession turns into a certainty. Finally, the government tries to reverse the downturn by increasing aggregate demand by lowering interest rates, increasing the money supply, reducing taxes and/or increasing government spending.

Further argument for a moderation on the effect of Covid-19 on US GDP statistics - and acknowledging in advance the unreliability of the medical and business data coming from China - there is tangential evidence that the country is returning to work (meaning "supply chain" effects will be less in the months ahead), and that the rate of growth of incidence of the disease is decelerating for the Chinese population at large (meaning"consumption" and "consumption patterns" will return to near-normal later in 2020). I note (possibly in error) that between start (late Dec 2019) to "finish" (end of Feb 2020) seems to suggest a 60-day period where Chinese business and social activity underwent dramatic change, after which a new normal began to be established, with recovery to follow. My estimate is that the same will happen here in the US.

The impact of the coronavirus is likely to be larger than forecasted by economists until now, given that most scenarios work on the basis of a containment by mid-March. While the number of new cases is going down in China, it's going up everywhere else. So while Q1 is mainly impacted by the slowing down of the Chinese economy and supply chain issues, Q2 is likely to be impacted by a slow down in demand. Aggressive counter measures in an election year, targeted more to maintain growth rather than to protect the population, are likely. If the outbreak is under control in the next couple of months, the drop in GDP growth will be limited to a few decimal points, so not enough to see a contraction. This assessment hinges however on a relatively good handling of the outbreak in the US, which is not a given considering the recent moves by the White House (shunning facts, declaring this a hoax, nominating Pence as coordinator, not filling vacant seats in key positions, etc.). To be monitored...

Other data today showed the goods trade deficit contracted sharply in January, with both imports and exports declining. While the narrowing goods trade deficit could be a boost to the calculation of GDP, a lot depends on how the coronavirus unfolds in the U.S. The Commerce Department said consumer spending increased 0.2% last month as unseasonably mild weather reduced demand for heating and undercut sales at clothing stores.
